Your Honor,

I stand before you today as David Lambert, acknowledging my guilt in driving while disqualified.

I deeply regret and take full responsibility for my actions. Two months ago, I was disqualified from driving due to four instances of speeding. Unfortunately, I neglected to consider the consequences of my behavior and drove to a supermarket while still disqualified. I sincerely apologize for disregarding the court's previous order and any inconvenience or harm I may have caused.

Prior to this incident, I had no criminal record. I have always strived to be a law-abiding citizen, and this isolated offense is an anomaly in my life. I truly feel embarrassed and sorry for letting this happen.

Looking back, I realize the severity of my mistake. I acknowledge that I failed to act in accordance with the court's instructions and I am truly remorseful for my behavior.

If given the opportunity, I am willing to do everything necessary to make amends and ensure compliance with the law. I would gladly undertake a driving course or any other measures that can improve my understanding of my legal responsibilities and prevent any future transgressions.

Once again, I apologize for my actions and any disappointment or inconvenience caused. I assure you, Your Honor, that I deeply regret my behavior.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Sincerely,
David Lambert
